    <p><strong>Tips to Live By - Advice from CES Exhibitor Advisory Board</strong><br> 
by Exhibitor Advisory Board</p>
    <p>Comprised of CES exhibitors, the <A href="/exhibitors/resources/advisoryBoard.asp" target=_blank>CES Exhibitor Advisory Board (EAB)</A> continues to serve on the behalf of all exhibiting companies, working collectively with the CES organization on everything from housing to transportation and labor to policy changes. Having the EAB provide feedback and suggestions to the CES team optimizes the experience for all. <BR><BR>Not only are we, the EAB, here to help guide CES staff, but we are also here to provide you with advice and guidance when navigating the exhibiting waters of CES. Recently, the EAB took some time out to develop a list of tips for CES exhibitors. Here are our top ten!<BR><BR><STRONG>Top&nbsp;10 Tips from the Exhibitor Advisory Board<BR></STRONG>
<OL type=1>
<LI><STRONG>Use social media in your marketing mix.</STRONG> It’s best to look into one to two mediums that work for your company. Use social media outlets like Facebook and Twitter to market your booth pre-show, and be sure to attach an ROI piece.<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Submit your orders for the early-bird discount.</STRONG> Be sure to pay close attention to discount deadline dates! We’ve found that only 64 percent of CES exhibitors take advantage of advance pricing, which means almost 1,000 of you pay 30 to 50 percent or more than you have to! Download the deadline checklist for your venue to help you stay on track. <BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Make sure you know your union jurisdiction and rules.</STRONG> Using union labor can be tricky when you aren’t aware of the rules and regulations. Review your exhibitor manual when it goes live in September.<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Be sure you have staff buy-in at CES.</STRONG> There is nothing worse than booth staff that doesn’t know what to do on-site. Use your internal communications team to relay the importance of your time at CES and create a staff guide that everyone on your team can refer to for help. In the December issue of the Exhibitor’s Source Newsletter, CES will provide a staff guide that will contain information on everything CES, including locations maps, dining options and badge pick-up info.<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>CES is a big tent. Use it!</STRONG> While on-site, you should leverage the efficiencies of the show to gather several different groups for meetings. You’re all in one place at the same time, and there is no easier place to gather than at CES. <BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Utilize the tools and information that CES makes available during your planning.</STRONG> CES provides a slew of info on CESweb.org. One of the best ways to find out all the tools available is by attending the CES Exhibitor Workshop webcast series. Here you will find tips on how to gain the right PR exposure, marketing tips and other exhibitor advice.<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Appeal to vendors for additional discounts.</STRONG> By taking the time to talk to vendors you’ll often times find that they are very willing to offer additional discounts. All you have to do is ask!<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Make sure you complete and customize your directory listing.</STRONG> It’s free to complete your directory listing, and it’s the best way for attendees to find you. Be sure to fill out as much information as you can. Also, make sure you have the correct contact info listed. More is always better in this instance.<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Design a photo opportunity in your booth.</STRONG> Nothing gets more exposure than a celebrity or an exciting product display. If possible, try to work these elements into your booth, and tell CES about it in advance so the details can be posted online.<BR></LI>
<LI><STRONG>Use your EAB as a source for advice and tips.</STRONG> Should you need, the EAB is available to talk with any exhibitor regarding the successes or issues you face in your exhibit experience. We encourage you to get in touch with the board at any time of the year (on-site at CES or via e-mail, phone, etc.) to not only keep us informed as your representatives, but also to learn more about the board and how to get involved. Learn who your Exhibitor Advisory Board is now.</LI></OL>
<P>CES can often be overwhelming, but it is also a very exciting time for our industry. Review our entire list of&nbsp; these helpful tips and we assure you that things will be made that much easier for you and your staff. We look forward to seeing you in 2010!</P></p>
